    <img
        class="hide-below-sm"
        alt=""
        width="3500"
        height="987"
        loading="lazy" js-autosizes        src="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20250505-revlimid-secondary-03desktophi.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=226&amp;q=75&amp;w=800&amp;s=982f9b3807f3a20bfaed3401bec67511"
        srcset="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20250505-revlimid-secondary-03desktophi.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=113&amp;q=75&amp;w=400&amp;s=2aaf62c6f725c25b56b4697c004d7f76 400w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20250505-revlimid-secondary-03desktophi.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=226&amp;q=75&amp;w=800&amp;s=982f9b3807f3a20bfaed3401bec67511 800w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20250505-revlimid-secondary-03desktophi.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=338&amp;q=75&amp;w=1200&amp;s=ef19cce2fd48fa8a42ea3e0812ba2adb 1200w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20250505-revlimid-secondary-03desktophi.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=367&amp;q=75&amp;w=1300&amp;s=57f3cbd0c581d2476b5dc15d1da437d9 1300w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20250505-revlimid-secondary-03desktophi.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=409&amp;q=75&amp;w=1450&amp;s=8726c1badd2914a5ce304027f757708a 1450w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20250505-revlimid-secondary-03desktophi.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=451&amp;q=75&amp;w=1600&amp;s=59491035a89ed24e278d059d72fbb3a1 1600w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20250505-revlimid-secondary-03desktophi.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=564&amp;q=75&amp;w=2000&amp;s=6be435a60d02f6aa9eb9d0b0794edaac 2000w"
                    />

            
    
<figcaption class="attribution">
    
    
    
    </figcaption>

</figure>

        
    
                    <h3    data-pp-id="58"
    data-pp-blocktype="heading"
    class="bb-heading bb-heading--chapter-hed"
    id="violent-arguments"
    >
    “Violent Arguments”
</h3>

        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="59.0">Word of Jimmy’s stunning recovery in Arkansas quickly made its way to the offices of Celgene Corp., located in a small corporate park in a rural patch of northern New Jersey.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="60.0">The company had just wrapped up a brutal year-end accounting, which showed losses of $27 million on revenue of just $1.1 million. Money was so tight that executives engaged in what one of them called “violent arguments” over whether to charge employees for coffee.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="61.0">Celgene had acquired the rights to thalidomide patents held by researchers at Rockefeller University in 1992. The company, which was new to pharmaceuticals, planned to use the experience of obtaining FDA approval for thalidomide to develop other drugs.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="62.0">“It wasn’t meant to be a blockbuster,” said Sol Barer, who started at the company in 1987 and later became CEO.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="63.0">When Celgene announced plans to develop the disgraced drug for new uses, the only analyst following the company on Wall Street dropped coverage and told Celgene officials they didn’t know what they were doing.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="64.0">The company thought the largest market would be as a treatment for AIDS patients experiencing dangerous weight loss. To win approval of the drug, however, Celgene selected a use that was already in practice in parts of the world for a small group of patients.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="65.0">In July 1998, the FDA approved thalidomide for the treatment of a painful complication of leprosy. It was a momentous decision, coming just a few decades after the drug caused so much harm.</p>

<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="65.1">The market for leprosy was tiny, but what happened with Jimmy in Arkansas changed everything for the company.</p>
        
    
                    

<figure
    data-pp-id="66"
    data-pp-blocktype="image"
    class="bb-image full center  wide-sm wrap 
                ">

    


            
    


